The options here are very lopsided. Consult Playbook can be a reasonable card to add some additional frontloading for your deck, but it's not typically a very exciting option, especially because of how it junks the deck in longer fights. It's nowhere near good enough to justify taking any of the trap downsides just to get a copy of it in your deck. Even weirder is that your other option also adds strong front-loaded damage and not only doesn't cost anything, but actively helps to remove basic strikes from your deck.

 If your deck has less than 3 strikes left in it, or if you have a truly awful mitigation package that can't handle the tackle damage, then you can pick leave, but reading is very commonly going to be the correct choice. The difference between having 4-5 strikes in your deck that deal 6 damage each and having 3 tackle+ that deal 16 damage (and deal 3 to you, which can be blocked) is enormous. To compensate, you may want to grab a few extra block cards/relics or some sustain to help make the tackles easier to play, but they should save you health already with how effectively they help delete short and medium hallway fights. Thinning your deck of strikes is also incredibly powerful, and frees you up to use your limited card removals on the remaining defends, and to have a much more streamlined deck overall. Astrolabe/Pandora's Box/Empty Cage are all boss relics that have similar effects of improving overall deck quality. Sure, if you are aggressively removing cards in act 1/2, and have already taken out 3+ strikes, this is a much less powerful event. It really depends on your playstyle, but I often prefer to use early shops to buy potions/cards rather than pursue card removal. Removing cards is much more impactful later in the run, when your deck has stronger cards to be drawing into.
